As Britain debates how to best incorporate European Union law into its own national legislation once it exits the bloc, the governments of Scotland and Wales said on Tuesday they will introduce their own "continuity laws" to prevent London weakening their autonomy as a result of Brexit. New laws will be debated by the devolved parliaments in Edinburgh and Cardiff in the coming days aimed at strengthening regional powers — including agriculture and fisheries — that are currently administered from Brussels because they fall within EU frameworks. The Scottish, Northern Irish and Welsh governments are concerned that the London parliament, which legislates on behalf of the whole of the UK, will seek to pass laws unilaterally that incorporate EU treaties into British national law, denying the three countries a say on key regional policies. Read more: UK must protect Scotch whisky post-Brexit, says Scottish official Send  Facebook   Twitter   Google+   Whatsapp   
