ential to open up a full-blown constitutional crisis, with some legal analysts accusing Scotland and Wales' governments of overreaching their powers, while the process of establishing whether the continuity laws are binding could take weeks or even months. Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland won devolved powers from London in the late 1990s after decades of demands for more autonomy. Plans to extend devolution to regions of England were never enacted. In the 2016 Brexit referendum, Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain in the EU, while Wales voted to leave. On Wednesday, EU Brexit negotiator Michel Barnier will unveil a long-awaited draft of the Brexit divorce treaty, which is likely to rankle with British ministers, as it seeks to hold the UK to European Court of Justice judgments in the settlement of disputes over the future trade relationship between the two sides. mm/se (AFP, Reuters)